        "subtype": "bot_message",
        "text": "*[Bug 19083] setGeneric(\"f\", \\(x) { standardGeneric(\"x\") }) makes generic with class 'nonstandardGenericFunction'*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19083>\n\nMikael Jagan (<mailto:jaganmn2@gmail.com|jaganmn2@gmail.com>) changed:\n\n           What    |Removed                     |Added\n----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n                 CC|                            |jaganmn2@gmail.com\n\n--- Comment #3 from Mikael Jagan (<mailto:jaganmn2@gmail.com|jaganmn2@gmail.com>) ---\nAfter\n\n```\nF &lt;- function (.) { standardGeneric(\"G\") }\nsetGeneric(\"G\", F)\n```\n\nI think that `body(F)` and `body(G)` should be identical, as currently. \nStripping braces, so that `body(G)` becomes `body(F)[[2L]]`, would violate the\nexpectation of users accustomed to parsing of calls to `function`, including\nones like `function (.) { UseMethod(\"G\") }`, which keeps braces.\n\nA smaller change would be to arrange for `setGeneric` to do\n`new(\"standardGeneric\", F, ...)` instead of `new(\"nonstandardGenericFunction\",\nF, ...)`.  Something like:\n\n```\nIndex: src\/library\/methods\/R\/RMethodUtils.R\n===================================================================\n--- src\/library\/methods\/R\/RMethodUtils.R        (revision 90180)\n+++ src\/library\/methods\/R\/RMethodUtils.R        (working copy)\n@@ -1215,7 +1215,10 @@\n\n .NonstandardGenericTest &lt;- function(body, fname, stdBody)\n {\n-    if(identical(body, stdBody))\n+    if(identical(body, stdBody) ||\n+       (is.call(body) &amp;&amp; length(body) == 2L &amp;&amp;\n+        identical(body[[1L]], quote(`{`)) &amp;&amp;\n+        identical(body[[2L]], stdBody)))\n         FALSE\n     else if(.recursiveCallTest(body, fname))\n         TRUE\n```\n\nThen, compared to current behaviour, `body(G)` is unchanged (still a call to\n`{`) but `class(G)` is `\"standardGeneric\"` instead of\n`\"nonstandardGenericFunction\"`.\n\nHowever, from reading and testing, I notice that nowhere in R is the\nstandard-nonstandard distinction actually used.  In particular, it seems\npossible to *remove* from **methods** these (documented as internal) class\ndefinitions\n\n```\nstandardGeneric\nstandardGenericWithTrace\nnonstandardGeneric\nnonstandardGenericWithTrace\nnonstandardGenericFunction\nnonstandardGroupGenericFunction\n```\n\n*keeping* in **methods** just these ones\n\n```\ngenericFunction\ngenericFunctionWithTrace\ngroupGenericFunction\ngroupGenericFunctionWithTrace\n```\n\nwithout changing documented behaviour.  Unfortunately, a small number of\npackages (15-20 across CRAN and BioC, according to a static analysis) have\nrelied inappropriately on **methods** internals by, e.g., testing `is(.,\n\"standardGeneric\")` where `is(., \"genericFunction\")` would have sufficed.\n\nHence I may propose a staged removal within R-core, leaving time between now\nand the release of R 4.7 to provide package maintainers with patches for their\ncode.  Fixing this \"bug\" with such a simplification, rather than a further\ncomplication of `setGeneric` logic, would be nice.  Well, it's just a proposal\nfor now and I'll want to explore more ...",
        "username": "r-bugs notifier",
        "icons": {
            "emoji": ":robot_face:"
        },
